  <h1 class="page-title">What Denison Owes Us</h1>
  <p class="page-subtitle">A Case for Institutional Accountability</p>
</section>

<!-- ESSAY BODY -->
<section style="padding:72px 60px;background:white">
  <div style="max-width:680px;margin:0 auto">

    <p style="font-family:'EB Garamond',serif;font-size:1.25rem;line-height:1.75;color:#2C2C2C;margin-bottom:2rem;font-style:italic">
      Every institution makes promises. The question is whether anyone is organized enough to hold them accountable when those promises go unmet.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      Denison University has, over the decades, made a number of explicit commitments to its Black students and alumni. Diversity statements. Hiring goals. Scholarship endowments. Support for the Black Student Union and alumni organizations like our own. Some of those commitments have been honored. Many have not been fully realized.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      This essay is not a condemnation. It is an invitation to clarity. What exactly did Denison commit to? What is the current state of those commitments? And what is the appropriate role of an organized alumni body — like the BAA — in holding the institution accountable?
    </p>

    <h2 style="font-family:'EB Garamond',serif;font-size:1.75rem;font-weight:500;margin:2.5rem 0 1rem;color:#2C2C2C">The Promise Problem</h2>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      Institutional promises are slippery things. They are often made in moments of pressure — after a campus incident, during a national reckoning, in response to organized student demands. And they are often made by administrators who will not be there five years later to see them through.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      This is not cynicism. It is a structural observation. Institutions do not remember the way people do. They remember through policy, through budget line items, through org charts, and through the people who stay long enough to carry institutional memory. If we don't track the promises, no one will.
    </p>

    <h2 style="font-family:'EB Garamond',serif;font-size:1.75rem;font-weight:500;margin:2.5rem 0 1rem;color:#2C2C2C">The Role of the BAA</h2>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      This is exactly why an organized alumni association matters. Not as a social club. Not as a fundraising appendage of the development office. But as an independent body with its own governance, its own resources, and its own long memory.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      The BAA is currently working to build exactly that. A Donor-Advised Fund we control. A scholarship process we govern. A newsletter and communications infrastructure that keeps our community informed year-round. The goal is not to replace Denison. The goal is to be strong enough — financially and organizationally — to be a real partner. Partners hold each other accountable.
    </p>

    <div style="background:var(--cream,#F9F5EE);border-left:4px solid #9B2335;padding:1.5rem 2rem;margin:2.5rem 0">
      <p style="font-family:'EB Garamond',serif;font-size:1.35rem;font-style:italic;line-height:1.5;color:#2C2C2C;margin:0">
        "The BAA is not a constituency to be managed. We are a constituency that manages."
      </p>
    </div>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      This piece is a beginning, not an end. In future issues, we will document specific commitments, track their progress, and report to our community what we find. That is the work. That is what accountability looks like.
    </p>

